letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":50,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Maud de Longchamp was born about 1240, in Wilton, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Henry de Longchamp, was 31 and her mother, Joan of Wilton, was 77. She married Reginald de Grey 1st Baron Grey de Wilton in 1258, in Wilton, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 21 November 1302, in Wilton, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 63."},"et":{"about 1240–21 November 1302":"umbes 1240–21. november 1302","1240–1302":"1240–1302","1240–1308":"1240–1308","1258–1323":"1258–1323","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1210–1264":"1210–1264","1165–Female":"11